  "prompt": "What is the difference between dynamic and kinematic viscosity?",
  "response": "The main differences between dynamic and kinematic viscosity are:\n\nDynamic Viscosity (Absolute Viscosity):\n1. Measures fluid's resistance to flow due to internal friction\n2. Represented by \u03bc (mu)\n3. Units: Pascal-second (Pa\u00b7s) or kg/(m\u00b7s)\n4. Describes the fluid's internal shear stress\n5. Depends on fluid's molecular structure and temperature\n\nKinematic Viscosity:\n1. Measures fluid's resistance to flow under gravity\n2. Represented by \u03bd (nu)\n3. Units: Square meters per second (m\u00b2/s)\n4. Calculated by dividing dynamic viscosity by fluid density\n5. Formula: \u03bd = \u03bc / \u03c1\n6. More commonly used in situations involving fluid flow and momentum transfer\n\nKey differences:\n- Dynamic viscosity directly measures fluid's resistance\n- Kinematic viscosity incorporates fluid density\n- Different units and calculation methods\n- Used in different fluid dynamics applications\n\nExample: Water at 20\u00b0C\n- Dynamic viscosity: 0.001 Pa\u00b7s\n- Kinematic viscosity: 1.004 \u00d7 10^-6 m\u00b2/s\n\nBoth are important in understanding fluid behavior and flow characteristics.",
